{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GTNyepnHT85tbVMTEk6WjA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The rate limiting is configured with `burst=5 nodelay`. That's the default behavior with `limit-rps` annotation. The `burst=5` means it allows bursting up to 5 requests without delay.\n\nAt 2 QPS (10 requests in 5 seconds), with a `burst=5` allowance and `nodelay`, all 10 requests at 2 QPS should be allowed by the burst. \n\nThe issue is that with `burst=5 nodelay`, the first 5 requests will be served even if they exceed the rate. Then the remaining requests at 2 QPS may also be served if the rate limiter has been replenishing.\nLet me reconsider how the token bucket actually works here. With a rate of 1 r/s and burst=5, the bucket starts empty and tokens are replenished at 1 per second. When requests arrive, each one costs a token, and with nodelay, requests are served immediately if tokens are available. So I need to trace through what happens as the 10 requests come in over those 5 seconds. So at 2 QPS I'm draining tokens faster than they replenish—consuming 2 per second while only gaining 1 back, creating a net loss of 1 token per second. Starting with 5 tokens in the burst bucket, by the time the 10th request arrives at t=4.5 seconds, I'd have roughly 0.5 tokens left before hitting the rate limit. Let me recalculate more carefully with the actual token consumption and replenishment rates.\n\nI'm clarifying how nginx's token bucket actually works—the burst parameter represents excess capacity beyond the configured rate, and with nodelay enabled, those excess requests get served immediately rather than queued. So with rate=1r/s and burst=5, the system can handle up to 6 concurrent requests (1 at the sustained rate plus 5 from the burst pool), but I need to trace through what happens when 10 requests arrive at 0.5-second intervals. Continuing through the calculation, at t=500ms the excess becomes 1.5, still under the burst limit of 5, and by t=1000ms it's 1.75. But I'm realizing nginx actually uses a different formula—it decrements the excess based on milliseconds elapsed times the rate per millisecond, rather than the exponential decay I was calculating.\n\nLet me reconsider with a clearer model: each request adds 1000 to the excess (since the rate is 1 request per second), and the excess decreases by 1 per millisecond. If the excess exceeds the burst threshold of 5000, the request gets rejected. Working through the timeline, at t=0 the excess jumps to 1000, then at t=500ms it's 1500, and by t=1000ms it reaches 2000—all still within the allowed burst capacity.\n\nContinuing this pattern, the excess keeps climbing by 500ms intervals: 2500 at t=1500ms, 3000 at t=2000ms, 3500 at t=2500ms, 4000 at t=3000ms, 4500 at t=3500ms, and finally hitting exactly 5000 at t=4000ms. But at t=4500ms, the excess would jump to 5500, which exceeds the burst limit, so that request gets rejected.\n\nWith a burst of 5 and rate of 1 request per second, I'm only seeing one rejection across 10 requests sent at 500ms intervals, but the math suggests at least 4 should be rejected. The issue is that the default burst value of 5 is too permissive—it allows too many requests through before hitting the limit. I need to reduce the burst multiplier to something smaller, like 1 or 0, to make the rate limiting stricter and actually reject more requests as expected. 1000, reject. But I need to clarify whether rejected requests still increment the excess counter or if it stays frozen at the pre-rejection value. Looking at how nginx actually computes this: it calculates excess as the old excess minus the time elapsed times the rate, plus the new request's cost. If that excess exceeds the limit, the request gets rejected, but the question is whether the excess value itself gets updated or reverts. I'm reconsidering the timing here—with the sleep between requests, maybe the burst window is absorbing all 10 requests within the 5-second span, which would explain why they all returned 200 instead of hitting the rejection threshold I calculated. Continuing through the remaining requests, the excess keeps growing by 400ms each interval, staying well under the 5000 limit, so all ten requests get served even with the burst constraint of 5.\n\nNow I need to figure out what burst value would actually cause rejections. If I want at least 4 of the 10 requests to be rejected, I need the excess to exceed the burst threshold by around request 7, which means solving for when 1000 + (n-1) × 400 exceeds the burst threshold.\n\nWorking through the math, I need burst_threshold < 3400, so burst < 3.4. That means setting burst=3 should do it. Let me verify this works by tracing through the excess calculations with 600ms intervals and burst=3 (threshold of 3000).\n\nThe first six requests all pass since their excess values stay at or below 3000, but request 7 hits 3400 which exceeds the threshold and gets rejected. After that, subsequent requests continue to be rejected depending on whether rejected requests update the excess counter or not.\n\nLet me test with a smaller burst value of 2 to see if I can reliably trigger at least 4 rejections. With burst=2, the first three requests pass, but request 4 already exceeds the limit at 2200, and then requests 5 through 10 all get rejected since the excess won't drop below 2000 at the given rate. That gives me 7 rejections total, which is solid.\n\nNow testing with burst=1 to see if that's even tighter—request 1 passes at exactly 1000, but request 2 jumps to 1400 which exceeds the limit.\n\nI'm realizing I need to check how nginx actually handles rejected requests in its token bucket implementation. Looking at the source code, when a request is rejected, the excess value isn't written back to shared memory, so the next request will calculate based on the old excess minus whatever time has elapsed. Let me trace through this with burst=1 at the 600ms intervals. So with 10 requests arriving at roughly 600ms intervals, I'd expect an alternating pattern of passes and fails—about 5 of each. But I need to recalculate more carefully since the last successful request stored excess at 800, not 1000, which changes how subsequent requests are evaluated. = 1400. 1400 > 1000, REJECT.\nreq 8 (t=4200ms): elapsed from last update (t=3000ms) = 1200ms. excess = 1000 - 1200 + 1000 = 800. 800 <= 1000, SERVE. Store 800.\nreq 9 (t=4800ms): elapsed = 600ms. excess = 800 - 600 + 1000 = 1200. 1200 > 1000, REJECT.\nreq 10 (t=5400ms): elapsed from last update (t=4200ms) = 1200ms. excess = 800 - 1200 + 1000 = 600. 600 <= 1000, SERVE. Store 600.\n\nWith burst=1: SERVE, REJECT, SERVE, REJECT,\n\nSERVE, SERVE, REJECT, SERVE, REJECT, SERVE = 4 REJECTs out of 10. That's exactly at the minimum threshold I need. I'm thinking about using `limit-burst-multiplier=1` to account for timing variations, though I could also try `limit-burst-multiplier=0` if needed—that would enforce strict 1r/s timing with no burst allowance at all. At 2 QPS with burst=0, every other request would get rejected. But I'm second-guessing the math here—if burst=0 means the limit is 0, then excess > 0 would reject everything, which doesn't make sense. I need to reconsider how nginx actually calculates this internally, since the rate and burst units might work differently than I'm thinking.\n\nLet me just go with burst=1 to be safe—that should give me some headroom without being too permissive, and I can test and adjust from there if needed.\n\nNow I need to verify that my 429 status code annotation is actually being applied in the location block, since the global nginx config defaults to 503. Let me check the actual rate-api ingress configuration to see if the override is in place.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1090,"cache_read_input_tokens":35013,"cache_crea